Reaction-diffusion are diffusions of chemicals coupled with rea=
ctions of those chemicals. They are expressed as partial differential equat=
ions, wich are integrated over a domain : usually, the unit square, but a d=
isc, a sphere or whatever shape. Indeed, Greg Turk did reaction-diffusions =
on horses, see &quot;Generating Textures on Arbitrary Surfaces Using Reaction-Di=
ffusion&quot;. To integrate a differential equations over a domain, you have to =
specify what happens at the border of the domain. Usually, on a square, peo=
ple considers that &#39;left&#39; is wrapped with &#39;right&#39;, &#39;top&#39; with &#39;bottom&#39;, whi=
ch explains the &quot;wallpaper&quot; look... But you might consider that outside the=
 square, chemicals concentration are just always 0. Chemicals are produced =
within the square and dissipate to the void at the square edge... No more w=
rapping, no more perfect tiling, thus no more &quot;wallpaper&quot; look.

